<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="529" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="45.[742,1335,989,1416]" lastBlockId="45.[127,1337,1422,2323]" pageId="45" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[742,992,1344,1377]" pageId="45" pageNumber="529">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 67-74 mm, tail 7-11 mm, ear 14-17 mm, hindfoot 12-15 mm, forearm 42-48 mm; weight 19-23 g. The Chocoan Nectar Batis the largest species of 
<taxonomicName box="[279,450,1462,1495]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Lonchophylla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="529" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Lonchophylla</taxonomicName>
. It is chocolate-brown to chestnut, with dorsal and individual ventral hairs bicolored; furis longer between shoulders (7-8 mm); and sparse fringe of hair occurs on free margin of uropatagium. Thumb is large (7-5-8: 
<quantity box="[1074,1163,1541,1574]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="45" pageNumber="529" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
), and calcar is shorter than foot. Skull is elongated and narrow, palate is long, and there is a postpalatine torus. Upper incisors of each rami of maxilla are separated by large gap, and I? and C'! are separated by small gaps. I? are pointed ventrally, C' are well developed, P* has well-developed lingual cusp, and lower incisors are trilobed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="529" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="45.[127,1337,1422,2323]" pageId="45" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[129,240,1738,1771]" pageId="45" pageNumber="529">Habitat.</emphasis>
Humid primary and secondary forests in Choco Biogeographic region (Pacific wet forests), western slope of Andes, and lowlands of 
<collectingCountry box="[965,1084,1782,1811]" name="Ecuador" pageId="45" pageNumber="529">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1160,1298,1782,1811]" name="Colombia" pageId="45" pageNumber="529">Colombia</collectingCountry>
at elevations of 500-1000 m. Average annual rainfall at known localities of the Chocoan Nectar Bat is ¢. 
<quantity box="[349,492,1857,1890]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="45" pageNumber="529" unit="mm" value="2800.0">2800 mm</quantity>
, and average annual temperature c.25°C. These localities comprise humid disturbed secondary forests that have been selectively logged without ever being fully cleared.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
